A year ago, December 22, I put up a post letting everyone know that after six and a half years, ITA retested my samples from the 2012 Olympic Games and IOC notified me that they found a banned substance. As I said in my earlier post, I passed two anti-doping tests, one prior to the Olympics and one right after them and for over six and a half years my results were considered negative! In a year since, nothing changed but now I have a lot more information.
.
In February 2019 sample "B" was tested as well as a control for more information. According to a statement from an independent expert, the amount of the substance found was so small that it could have been equal to a single ingestion through food or a supplement and could not have had any influence on the results. Trying to check all supplements used over seven years ago would be impossible at this point and absolutely pointless as it would still show in the lab tests. By the rules of the Olympic Committee, ANY amount is equal to automatic disqualification.
.
By the rules of IOC and IWF, my results from the 2012 Olympics were void.
.
How do I feel about this? A year ago I was shocked and sad due to these findings but at this moment I understand that life goes on and I'm focusing on new projects and of course my family.
.
What do I think about all this? I think I'll have to put that in my book.
All I know is that no matter what, I will always share my knowledge and the love of the sport!

Foot placement on one straight line is one of the top mistakes made by athletes when performing the Split Jerk. To understand the problem, let's associate our positions with geometric figures. When setting our legs on the same line (on the same rail), our body looks like an unstable upside down triangle. When we spread our feet wider (on two rails) the width of our shoulders, we get a rectangle that is a lot more stable on the ground.
It‚Äôs better to solve this problem during our warm-up with an empty bar. To do this, I recommend putting a board (see the video) to make work on our muscle memory. The width of the board is approximately 1/2 of the width of your shoulders. 3-4 sets, 6 times will be enough to give us the necessary feeling.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
This exercise needs the static work performance for a time. Holding the bar with heavy weight leads to the development of the starting position before the JERK from the chest, and also makes it possible to work out the muscular feeling and balance of all parts of the body with a heavy weight on the chest. Performing this exercise well, helps to cope with a feeling of fear of the weight and pressure of the barbell in preparation for JERK from the chest, and also strengthens the stabilizers.
